#Experiencing music emotions through movement

Code and data for our *neuroscience and musicology* paper:

**"Evaluating the motor cortex’s role in generating emotion by comparing cortical 
inhibition using Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (TMS) to a sham control session"**

By [Sofia Knopf](University of British Columbia Okanagan), [Sarah Kraeutner](https://thenimbl.com/) 
(University of British Columbia Okanagan), and 
[Anja Cui](https://ucrisportal.univie.ac.at/en/persons/anja-xiaoxing-cui/) (University of Vienna) 


All experimental results can be reproduced using the code and data in this repository. However, no raw data has been provided as it contains sensitive human data. 
Feel free to contact Sarah Kraeutner (corresponding author) by [sarah.kraeutner@ubc.ca] 
if you have any questions about our work. 

**Abstract**

Music has the power to move us both physically and emotionally. 
Research suggests a correlation between primary motor cortex (M1) activity and emotional production. 
However, the causal relationship between M1 involvement and emotional processing has not yet been established using continuous theta-burst stimulation (cTBS). 
To address this gap, the present within-subjects study will examine the effects on emotional responses to music following M1 inhibition. 
Participants (N = 20, right-handed) will attend two laboratory sessions involving either active, or sham stimulation serving as a control. 
cTBS will be applied to the contralateral M1 to modulate motor pathway activity. Following stimulation, participants will listen to pre-rated instrumental music clips 
balanced for valence and arousal and will rate their emotional responses using standardized valence and arousal scales. 
These findings may advance applications in well-being and neurorehabilitation, where music is used to enhance emotional health and restore motor function after neurological injury.

**Directory**

* `data/` contains all the data used in this project. However, only processed de-identified data was incdluded as public sharing of raw data is against ethics. This subdirectory contains a data dictionary. 
* `scripts/` contains source code for the within-participant valence and arousal ratings across active and sham TMS sessions. This contains files to generate the models and plots in the paper.

**Requirments** 

* R version 4.4.2
* openxlsx 

